{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478621"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.3,0.49,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10217"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10217"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56614"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1847"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"9617"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49484"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-hour-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with excessive oral secretions and choking episodes when attempting to feed. He was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy. He has no other medical history and takes no medications. His birth weight was 3.2 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 140/min, respiratory rate 45/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is pooling of secretions in the mouth. Attempts to pass a nasogastric tube are unsuccessful at 10 cm. Chest X-ray shows a coiled nasogastric tube in the upper mediastinum and a gaseous abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely anatomical abnormality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Isolated oesophageal atresia","Oesophageal atresia with proximal tracheo-oesophageal fistula","Oesophageal atresia with distal tracheo-oesophageal fistula","Isolated tracheo-oesophageal fistula","Oesophageal atresia with proximal and distal tracheo-oesophageal fistula"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis newborn presents with classic features of oesophageal atresia (OA): excessive oral secretions, choking with feeds, and inability to pass a nasogastric tube. The presence of a gaseous abdomen on X-ray indicates there must be a connection between the trachea and distal oesophagus allowing air to reach the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal atresia with distal tracheo-oesophageal fistula\u003C/strong\u003E (Type C) is the most common form, accounting for approximately 85% of all cases. In this type, there is a blind-ending proximal oesophageal pouch and a fistula connecting the trachea to the distal oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsolated oesophageal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E (Type A) accounts for about 8% of cases. This would present with a similar upper pouch but would show an absent or gasless abdomen on X-ray as there is no connection to allow air to reach the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal atresia with proximal tracheo-oesophageal fistula\u003C/strong\u003E (Type B) is rare, occurring in less than 1% of cases. This would also show an absent or gasless abdomen on X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsolated tracheo-oesophageal fistula\u003C/strong\u003E (Type E or H-type) occurs in about 4% of cases. These patients typically have a patent oesophagus and would allow passage of a nasogastric tube.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal atresia with proximal and distal tracheo-oesophageal fistula\u003C/strong\u003E (Type D) is very rare, occurring in less than 1% of cases. While this would show a gaseous abdomen, it is much less common than Type C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAssociated anomalies are common in oesophageal atresia, particularly cardiac defects, and are often remembered using the VACTERL association (Vertebral, Anal, Cardiac, Tracheo-oesophageal, Renal, and Limb abnormalities).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type C oesophageal atresia (with distal tracheo-oesophageal fistula) accounts for 85% of all cases.","Inability to pass a nasogastric tube and excessive oral secretions are key diagnostic features of oesophageal atresia.","Chest X-ray showing a coiled tube in the upper mediastinum confirms the diagnosis of oesophageal atresia."],"references":["van Lennep M, Singendonk MMJ, Dall\u0027Oglio L, Gottrand F, Krishnan U, Terheggen-Lagro SWJ, Omari TI, Benninga MA, van Wijk MP. Oesophageal atresia. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2019 Apr 18;5(1):26. doi: 10.1038/s41572-019-0077-0. Erratum in: Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024 Mar 22;10(1):24. doi: 10.1038/s41572-024-00513-1. PMID: 31000707."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56614"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56614"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T12:30:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T12:31:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10217"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71143"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type"